{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4925308e-00f7-4ea0-9a01-2de8c14996e4","content":"**MSTest.Sdk 4.x defaults to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP) as the runner**, dropping the VSTest adapter that `vstest.console` needs for test discovery.\n\nIn 3.8.0, the VSTest adapter was included by default. In 4.1.0, `EnableMicrosoftTestingPlatform` defaults to `true`, so the VSTest adapter is no longer shipped.\n\n**You have two options:**\n\n1. **Migrate your CI to `dotnet test`** (recommended — it supports MTP natively):\n   ```\n   dotnet test TestProject.csproj\n   ```\n\n2. **Opt back into VSTest mode** by adding this to your `.csproj`:\n   ```xml\n   <EnableMicrosoftTestingPlatform>false</EnableMicrosoftTestingPlatform>\n   ```\n\nOption 1 is the forward-looking path; option 2 is a quick unblock if you can't change your CI pipeline right now.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8daeeb0a-ed56-4c0f-9f8c-1f1572cea0de","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a known breaking change in MSTest.Sdk. Starting with MSTest.Sdk 3.x, MSTest introduced support for Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP) as an alternative to VSTest. In earlier versions (like 3.8.0), the VSTest adapter was still included by default, so `vstest.console` could discover and run tests.\n\nIn MSTest.Sdk 4.x, the default runner changed to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP), and the VSTest adapter is no longer included by default. This means `vstest.console` can no longer discover tests because the VSTest adapter bridge is not present.\n\n\nTo work around this, you can either switch to `dotnet test` or run the test executable directly, since both work natively with MTP. The key change is that `EnableMicrosoftTestingPlatform` now defaults to `true` in 4.x, and the VSTest adapter package is no longer referenced by default.","outputTokens":663,"requestId":"4C1D:6C08C:E05974:10B8C8F:6A014802"},"id":"2a33ccac-3065-4b4b-a51c-e8f56f4c4f3d","timestamp":"2026-05-11T03:08:00.308Z","parentId":"5fdd481b-e2d8-4d4b-a0db-36911f0bddfb"}
